ck Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs. William Orrell was born in 1214, in Wigan, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom. She married William de Orrell in 1234, in Wigan, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son."},"et":{"1214–":"1214–Surnud","1200–1278":"1200–1278","–1300":"–1300","1214–Female":"1214–Surnud","1214":"1214","1234":"1234","1300":"1300","1278":"1278","1200":"1200","Orrell Hall, Wigan, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom":"Wigan, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1214–":"1214–Kuollut","1200–1278":"1200–1278","–1300":"–1300","1214–Female":"1214–Kuollut","1214":"1214","1234":"1234","1300":"1300","1278":"1278","1200":"1200","Orrell Hall, Wigan, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom":"Wigan, Lancashire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1214–":"1214–Décédée","1200–1278":"1200–1278","–1300":"–1300","1214–Female":"1214–Décédée","1214":"1214","1234":"1234","1300":"1300","1278":"1278","1200":"1200","Orrell Hall, Wigan, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom":"Wigan, Lancashire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Mrs. William Orrell est née en 1214, à Wigan, Lancashire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni. Elle a épousé William de Orrell en 1234, à Wigan, Lancashire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni. Ils ont eu au moins 1 fils."},"de":{"1214–":"1214–Verstorben","1200–1